Port Scanning Detected (1)
TimeSource IPTargetScan TypePorts ScannedSeverityAction
2026-01-09 21:19:04 192.168.100.203 Vertical 15 (443) Low
What is Vertical Port Scan?

Definition

A vertical port scan targets multiple ports on the same host. Source 192.168.100.203 scanned 15 different ports, attempting to discover all available services.

Why is this a problem?

Port scans are reconnaissance activities that precede attacks. Attackers use scans to map your network, identify running services, and find vulnerabilities to exploit. While scanning itself may not be harmful, it indicates malicious intent and often precedes actual attacks.

How was it detected?

The tool detected 192.168.100.203 scanning 15 ports/hosts in a short time period, with connection attempts that match port scanning patterns (rapid SYN packets without completing handshakes).

Wireshark Filter

Use this filter in Wireshark to examine the specific traffic:

ip.src == 192.168.100.203 and tcp.flags.syn == 1

Recommended Actions

1. Apply the filter to see the scan traffic. 2. Use 'tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0 and ip.src == 192.168.100.203' to see SYN packets. 3. Check for responses with 'tcp.flags.reset == 1' (closed ports) or 'tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 1' (open ports). 4. Identify which ports were targeted using 'Statistics â†’ Conversations â†’ TCP'. 5. Block source IP 192.168.100.203 at the firewall. 6. Review firewall rules to ensure only necessary ports are exposed. 7. Implement IDS/IPS to detect and block scanning. 8. Check if any services on scanned ports have known vulnerabilities.
TCP Retransmissions (210)
SourceDestinationPortAction
192.168.100.203:49901 35.223.238.178:443 443
What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

How was it detected?

The tool identified 1 retransmission events for the flow 192.168.100.203 â†’ 35.223.238.178 by analyzing TCP sequence numbers and detecting duplicate packets or packets marked with retransmission flags.

Wireshark Filter

Use this filter in Wireshark to examine the specific traffic:

tcp.analysis.retransmission and ip.addr == 192.168.100.203 and ip.addr == 35.223.238.178

Recommended Actions

1. Open the PCAP file in Wireshark and apply the filter above. 2. Examine the Time column to identify when retransmissions occur. 3. Check the TCP Stream (right-click packet â†’ Follow â†’ TCP Stream) to see the full conversation. 4. Investigate network links, switches, routers, and QoS settings between 192.168.100.203 and 35.223.238.178. 5. Check for bandwidth saturation, interface errors, or duplex mismatches. 6. Use ping and traceroute to test connectivity and latency.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

Why is this a problem?

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

How was it detected?

35.223.238.178:443 192.168.100.203:50211 50211
What is High TCP Retransmission?

Definition

TCP retransmission occurs when a packet sent by one host is not acknowledged by the receiving host within a certain time frame (RTO - Retransmission Timeout). The sender then resends the packet to ensure reliable delivery.

Why is this a problem?

Excessive retransmissions (1 detected) indicate network packet loss, congestion, or high latency. This leads to degraded application performance, slower data transfer speeds, and poor user experience. Applications may appear sluggish or unresponsive.

How was it detected?

The tool identified 1 retransmission events for the flow 35.223.238.178 â†’ 192.168.100.203 by analyzing TCP sequence numbers and detecting duplicate packets or packets marked with retransmission flags.

What is High Round-Trip Time (RTT)?

Definition

Round-Trip Time (RTT) is the time it takes for a packet to travel from source to destination and back. The flow between 192.168.100.203 and 35.223.238.178 has an average RTT of 127.25 ms, which is considered high.

Why is this a problem?

High RTT (127.25 ms) causes slow application response times, delayed page loads, and poor user experience. Real-time applications like VoIP, video conferencing, and online gaming are severely affected. Each request-response cycle is delayed, multiplying the impact.

How was it detected?

The tool calculated RTT by measuring the time between TCP data packets and their corresponding ACK packets for the flow 192.168.100.203 â†” 35.223.238.178.

Protocol Analysis Guide

Understanding Network Protocols

TCP Handshakes

Normal Behavior: TCP uses a three-way handshake to establish connections:

  1. SYN: Client sends SYN packet to server
  2. SYN-ACK: Server responds with SYN-ACK
  3. ACK: Client sends final ACK to complete handshake

Abnormal Behavior: Failed handshakes occur when SYN packets receive no response (server down/firewalled) or receive RST (connection refused).

Wireshark Filters:

  • tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0 - See SYN packets (connection attempts)
  • tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 1 - See SYN-ACK packets (server responses)
  • tcp.flags.reset == 1 - See RST packets (connection refused/aborted)
  • tcp.analysis.flags - See TCP analysis flags (retransmissions, out-of-order, etc.)
HTTP/HTTPS

Normal Behavior: HTTP requests receive 2xx (success) or 3xx (redirect) responses.

Abnormal Behavior: 4xx errors indicate client-side issues (404 Not Found, 403 Forbidden). 5xx errors indicate server-side failures (500 Internal Server Error, 503 Service Unavailable).

Wireshark Filters:

  • http.response.code >= 400 - See all HTTP errors
  • http.response.code >= 500 - See server errors only
  • http.request.method == "GET" - See GET requests
  • http.request.method == "POST" - See POST requests
  • ssl.handshake.type == 1 - See HTTPS ClientHello packets
DNS

Normal Behavior: DNS queries receive responses with answer records. Response time is typically under 100ms.

Abnormal Behavior: NXDOMAIN (domain doesn't exist), timeouts (no response), excessive queries to random domains (DGA malware), or queries to suspicious domains.

Wireshark Filters:

  • dns.flags.response == 0 - See DNS queries
  • dns.flags.response == 1 - See DNS responses
  • dns.flags.rcode == 3 - See NXDOMAIN responses
  • dns.time > 1 - See slow DNS responses (>1 second)
  • dns.qry.name contains "suspicious" - Search for specific domains
ARP

Normal Behavior: ARP requests receive a single response mapping an IP to a MAC address.

Abnormal Behavior: Multiple MAC addresses claiming the same IP (conflict), excessive ARP requests (scanning), or gratuitous ARP from unexpected sources (spoofing).

Wireshark Filters:

  • arp.opcode == 1 - See ARP requests (who-has)
  • arp.opcode == 2 - See ARP replies (is-at)
  • arp.duplicate-address-detected - See ARP conflicts
  • arp.src.proto_ipv4 == 192.168.1.1 - See ARP for specific IP

Wireshark Filter Guide

How to Use Wireshark Filters with This Report

ðŸ“‹ Quick Start

  1. Copy the Filter: Click the "Copy" button next to any Wireshark filter in this report
  2. Open Wireshark: Load your PCAP file in Wireshark
  3. Apply Filter: Paste the filter into the display filter bar at the top
  4. Press Enter: Wireshark will show only the packets matching the filter

ðŸ” Extracting Filters from Report Data

This report contains network analysis data in JavaScript variables. You can extract additional filters by:

  1. View Page Source: Press Ctrl+U (or Cmd+Option+U on Mac) to view the HTML source
  2. Search for Data: Press Ctrl+F and search for:
    • var timelineData - Event timeline with IPs, ports, and event types
    • var networkData - Flow data for retransmissions and issues
    • var sankeyData - Top-level traffic flow aggregations
  3. Identify IPs and Ports: Look for IP addresses and port numbers in the data
  4. Build Your Filter: Use the examples below to construct custom filters

ðŸ“ Common Filter Patterns

Basic Flow Filters

Traffic between two IPs:

ip.addr == 192.168.1.100 and ip.addr == 8.8.8.8

Specific port:

ip.addr == 192.168.1.100 and tcp.port == 443

Source to destination:

ip.src == 192.168.1.100 and ip.dst == 8.8.8.8
TCP Analysis Filters

TCP Retransmissions:

tcp.analysis.retransmission and ip.addr == 192.168.1.100

TCP SYN packets (connection attempts):

tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0

Failed handshakes (SYN with no response):

tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0 and ip.addr == 192.168.1.100

TCP resets:

tcp.flags.reset == 1
DNS Filters

DNS queries:

dns and dns.flags.response == 0

DNS responses:

dns and dns.flags.response == 1

Specific domain query:

dns.qry.name == "example.com"

DNS failures (NXDOMAIN):

dns.flags.rcode == 3
Security Filters

Port scan detection:

ip.src == 192.168.1.100 and tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0

SYN flood (DDoS):

ip.dst == 192.168.1.1 and tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0

ARP conflicts:

arp and arp.src.proto_ipv4 == 192.168.1.100

Suspicious high-port connections:

tcp.dstport > 49152 and tcp.flags.syn == 1
HTTP/HTTPS Filters

HTTP errors (4xx, 5xx):

http.response.code >= 400

Specific error code:

http.response.code == 404

TLS/SSL traffic:

tls and ip.addr == 192.168.1.100

TLS handshake:

tls.handshake.type == 1

ðŸ’¡ Pro Tips

  • Combine Filters: Use and, or, and parentheses: (ip.addr == 192.168.1.100) and (tcp.port == 443 or tcp.port == 80)
  • Exclude Traffic: Use ! or not: ip.addr == 192.168.1.100 and !dns
  • Follow TCP Stream: Right-click a packet â†’ Follow â†’ TCP Stream to see the entire conversation
  • Save Filters: Click the bookmark icon in Wireshark to save frequently used filters
  • Time-based Filtering: Use frame.time >= "2024-01-01 10:00:00" to filter by time

ðŸŽ¯ Using Timeline Data

The timelineData variable in this report contains events with:

  • source - Source IP address
  • target - Destination IP address
  • type - Event type (TCP SYN, DNS Query, etc.)
  • timestamp - Unix timestamp

Example from timeline: {"source":"192.168.100.203","target":"8.8.8.8","type":"TCP SYN"}

Wireshark filter: ip.src == 192.168.100.203 and ip.dst == 8.8.8.8 and tcp.flags.syn == 1 and tcp.flags.ack == 0

ðŸ“Š Using Sankey Flow Data

The sankeyData shows aggregated flows between network segments:

  • Internal â†’ Gateway: ip.src == 192.168.0.0/16 and ip.dst == 192.168.1.1
  • Gateway â†’ Internet: ip.src == 192.168.1.1 and not ip.dst == 192.168.0.0/16
  • All Internal Traffic: ip.src == 192.168.0.0/16 and ip.dst == 192.168.0.0/16
